                        <div id="project-energy" class="project-detail hidden">
                            <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mb-2">AI Energy Consumption Policy Brief</h3>
                            <p class="text-slate-600 mb-6">
                                <strong>I authored a policy brief analyzing AI's environmental footprint, proposing NIST RMF-adapted governance frameworks to mitigate energy risks and promote sustainable scaling.</strong> 
                                Highlighted data center growth (from 1.9% to 4%+ of U.S. electricity) and global projections (up to 21% by 2030), advocating for regulatory resilience.
                            </p>
                            <h4 class="font-semibold text-slate-700 mb-2">Key Skills Demonstrated</h4>
                            <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-slate-600 space-y-1 mb-6">
                                <li><strong>AI Policy Research:</strong> Quantified energy/carbon impacts from data centers and LLM training</li>
                                <li><strong>Governance Innovation:</strong> Adapted NIST RMF for sustainability mandates and efficiency benchmarks</li>
                                <li><strong>Thought Leadership:</strong> Influenced AI labs/regulators on defensible energy strategies</li>
                            </ul>
                            <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-6">
                                <div><h5 class="font-medium text-slate-700 mb-2">Challenge</h5><p class="text-sm text-slate-600">AI's rapid growth drives data center energy use (176 TWh in U.S. by 2023, projected 7-12% of electricity by 2028), risking regulatory backlash and sustainability gaps without proactive frameworks.</p></div>
                                <div><h5 class="font-medium text-slate-700 mb-2">My Role</h5><p class="text-sm text-slate-600">Reseached trends/projections; authored brief with NIST-based mitigations for state-level adoption and corporate compliance.</p></div>
                            </div>
